Title : Vsevolod Sharonov
Text : '''Vsevolod Sharonov''' (1901–1964) was a Russian astronomer.

== Life ==

He was born on March 10, 1901 in St. Petersburg.<ref name="books.google.co.in">{{cite book|title=Encyclopaedic biography of the world great physicists|author=Basu, S.K.|publisher=Global Vision Publishing House|isbn=9788182201569|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=j0xD9icpTwcC|page=1453|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> 
He died on November 26, 1964 in Leningrad.<ref name="books.google.co.in"/>

== Education ==

He graduated from gymnasium in 1918<ref name="books.google.co.in"/> and graduated from Petrograd University in 1926.<ref name="books.google.co.in"/>

== Career ==

The bulk of his work was done at [[Pulkovo Observatory]].<ref name="books.google.co.in"/> He was appointed as a professor at the [[University of Leningrad]] and was the director of the Astronomical Observatory.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=New Scientist|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|issn=0262-4079|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=-ebu8AZManEC|page=594|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> His main focus and interest was in the study of planets and atmospheric optics.

== Honours ==

The following are named after him:

* [[Sharonov (Martian crater)]]
* Asteroid [[2416 Sharonov]]
* [[Sharonov (lunar crater)]]

== Bibliography ==

He published over 300 research papers in his lifetime.<ref name="harvard">{{Cite journal|url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1969IrAJ....9..166.|bibcode=1969IrAJ....9..166.|title=OBITUARY: Vsevolod V. Sharonov; Fernand Baldet; Erich Schoenberg|page=166|accessdate=2014-10-31|journal=Irish Astronomical Journal|volume=9|date=December 1969}}</ref>

He is the author of:

* ''The Nature of the Planets''<ref name="Sharonov1964">{{cite book|author=Vsevolod Vasilʹevich Sharonov|title=The Nature of Planets: (Priroda Planet)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hcu7AAAAIAAJ|date=1964|publisher=Israel Program for Scientific Translations}}</ref>
* ''Measurement and Calculations of the Visibility of Distant Objects''
* ''Mars''
* ''The Sun and its Observation''

